Title : The Heroes (band)
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}
{{refimprove|date=April 2014}}

The Heroes were a rock band formed in 1979, with Chris Bradford and Mark Hankins on guitar and vocals. The line-up was completed by Pete Lennon (lead guitar), Dave Powell (drums) and ex-Randy band-member Brian (Wally) Wallis on bass guitar.<ref name=RYM01>{{cite web|title=Heroes personnel|url=http://rateyourmusic.com/artist/heroes|work=rateyourmusic.com|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>  <ref name=GDZ>{{cite web|title=The Heroes @ Glorydaze|url=http://gdm.glorydazemusic.com/articles.php?article_id=2743|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> <ref name=RAN>{{cite web|title=Randy - Mark Hankins bio|url=http://www.lynpaulwebsite.org/NS-Hankins.htm|work=Lyn Paul website|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>  <br />
Although primarily a recording group, they performed a tour of Germany with [[Dr. Feelgood (band)|Dr. Feelgood]], playing the Olympianhalle in Munich and the notorious [[Top Ten Club]] in Hamburg.<br />
Playing good time rock and roll, the five piece recorded an album of ten Bradford penned songs: ‘Border Raiders’ in 1980, plus a single ‘Some Kind of Women b/w 10 % Will Do’ all released on the Polydor label. 
<ref name = "Heroes BR">{{cite web|title=Border Raiders @ Allmusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/border-raiders-mw0000846589/credits|work=allmusic.com database|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> 

== Personnel ==

* [[Chris Bradford (rock musician)|Chris Bradford]] - guitar, lead vocals
* Mark Hankins - guitar, vocals
* Pete Lennon - lead guitar
* Dave Powell - drums
* Brian (Wally) Wallis - bass guitar
* [[Pip Williams]] - producer

